Not only does it have ceramide which is a super hydrating ingredient, but it also features Centella Asiatica as well as oatmeal, which it's great for people like me who have sensitive skin. I found that the formula was nice and lightweight, didn't feel tacky or sticky whatsoever, and because of its milky formula it was nice and hydrating for my super sensitive and dry leaning skin. Right here I'm using it my favorite way, directly applying it to my clean hands and my clean face, so that I'm not wasting any product on a cotton round. I have to say that the scent was very light and minimal as well, although I would say it leans on the floral side, but overall I was very happy with how hydrating this product was.

2023 was a year of figuring shit out… What works, what doesn’t.  What I want more of, what I want less of.  What deserves more attention, what deserves zero attention. . This is my takeaway: * I did a full year of art markets and exhausted myself on all fronts. This year, I’m not doing any markets and I will only be selling art online. The feeling of absolute freedom is wonderful. * I quit drinking in July because hangovers fucking suck and it was a huge cause of procrastination, depression and general laziness.  * I visited my family a lot and more importantly- spent the majority of that time with my Grandma. She was the single-best part of my childhood and it helped me focus on those times, rather than spiraling into childhood trauma. She truly is the reason of who I am as an adult.  * I went on a lot of hot girl walks. Sometimes solo, other times I went with friends (who are also super busy) and used that time to catch up. Even though I have been slacking on them lately, it has become something that I absolutely crave doing. * I stopped listening to true crime podcasts. I am well aware that the world is a weird place for women but I’m fucking tired of feeling anxious about leaving my house. Running errands has always been fun for me. Wake and bake, grab my planner and off I go…But these TC podcasts really sucked the fun right out of them. Over it. All of this is to say: Happy new year and I hope you can use 2024 to figure your shit out and make life easier for yourself.  . #getyourhandsdirty #agenda #planner #plannerdecoration #journal #journalcommunity #happynewyear2024 #mixedmediaart #mixedmediaartist #mushroomart #collageartwork #collageart #magazinecutouts #dailyplanner #positivethinking #betterlifestyle #healthylifestyle #mentalhealthart #asheville #ashevilleartist #createdtocreate #journalcommunity #organizeyourlife #agenda2024 #bulletjournals #creativejournaling

This is something to keep in mind when searching for tallow based products. What type of rendering method does the company use? Do they purchase their tallow from a third party supplier? Grass fed tallow contains naturally occurring vitamins A, D, E and K which are only found in animal products and they are essential for our health. 3. Tallow is identical to the oils we produce as humans (sebum) making it bioavailable to us and easy to absorb. In fact, the word sebum actually means tallow in Latin. voice_to_text: California governor Gavin Newsome just passed a law forcing toy stores to have a gender neutral section for children. Toy stores have the Pink Girls section and the Blue Boys section now. A New California law going into effect at the start of the year will require large retail stores with 500 or more employees statewide have a gender neutral section for toys. If the law is violated, a store could first be handed a 250 dollar fine, then a 500 dollar fine for a second offense. We're not affected by the law, but I say yay! It's not called Vogue, it's called American Freedom. This new law does not take away a boys or girls section. It only adds the gender neutral section, putting similar products that had been marketed for girls or boys side by side in an aisle along with toys that could appeal to everyone. Those with the California Family Council say enough is enough. They believe Sacramento needs to start focusing more on things that matter, unless on tours. A little crazy that Sacramento seems so intent on breaking down the distinctions and differences between men and women, between boys and girls. It's not enough that we are having gender neutral bathrooms. We're even trying to extend that to the toy section.

Reading U.S. History: Clarence Manion and the Flexowriter (Before the Storm by Rick Perlstein) #booktok #nonfiction #readingushistory #conservative #democrat #republican
voice_to_text: this week I'm reading the first six chapters of before the storm by Rick Pearlstein this is Pearlstein's book on Berry Goldwater and the early days of the modern conservative movement in the United States I'm reading this with my reading US history book club you can join the discord for that at the 🔗 today I wanted to talk a little bit about one of the early central characters who is actually not Berry Goldwater Clarence Manion that would be this gentleman right here now Clarence Manion became a key figure in the 1950s and early 1960s as a conservative movement began to take shape and eventually take over the Republican Party but in the 1930s he was a Democrat in Indiana he actually ran in the democratic primary for a US House seat in Indiana twice in the 1930s so how did this Indiana Democrat become a key figure in the emergence of a conservative Republican in Arizona well it had a lot to do with this guy up until the 1960s both the democratic and Republican parties had Liberal and conservative wings the conservative wing of the Democratic Party was generally located in the segregationist Deep South although not exclusively there were plenty of racist Democrats all over the country and also other conservatives who found their home in the Democratic Party but were increasingly uncomfortable with the Liberal direction that the Roosevelt administration was taking the party Manion was an isolationist and joined the America First *Committee (sic) in an era where the Roosevelt administration was getting the United States into World War 2 and he and many conservatives reacted very strongly against a Supreme Court case in 1942 Wickard v Filburn that was a case that decided that the federal government has the ability to tell farmers what they can and can't grow on their own land people like Manion and his fellow travelers felt like this was gross overreach of the federal government but they didn't have a political home to express those ideas The Democratic Party owned the federal government at this time and was being driven by a popular wartime president who was making compromise decisions with the more conservative in southern wing of his party but generally keeping the country in a fairly Liberal policy space The Republican Party was generally more pro business but was dominated by an eastern establishment who would coalesce around Eisenhower who was fairly moderate by the mid 1950s Manion and his political allies believed that if they could pry out the conservative wings of both the democratic and Republican parties they might have enough of a coalition to start winning elections their thought at the time was that they would have to form a new political party would take them a little bit longer to realize that it would be easier to just take over one of the parties and that would end up being the Republican Party and they ended up getting a lot of help on that front based on how Democrats like Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson reacted to the civil rights movement in the 1960s but that's putting the car before the horse right now in the late 1940s and early 1950s we've got this guy Clarence Manion who has this feeling that there are conservatives out there like him that if he could just organize they could start winning election and what I wanted to focus on is this thing what is this thing it's a Flexowriter it's an automated typewriter that you would feed punch tape into kind of like a player piano and it could replicate letters it's basically like a proto Xerox machine Manion ended up being a radio talk show host yes radio talk show host have always had an awful lot of influence in the conservative movement and instead of taking sponsorships he bought one of these automated typewriters and just started sending thousands of letters to family friends friends of friends anyone that he could find who might be interested in supporting the Conservative Radio Forum that he was developing this is something that I think anyone who aspires to political change and wants to get into political organizing should take note of it's not for nothing that people say that amateurs study strategy and professional study logistics Manion used the most advanced technology of his day to start building a mailing list and Manion's list itself and the very idea of reaching out directly in a targeted way to specific voters and building lists of them would be an incredibly important organizational tool in the conservative movement Karl Rove yes that Karl Rove got his start by being the king of Republican direct mail in Texas when conservatives founded the Moral Majority in 1979 one of their key organizational tools was Jerry Falwell's Old Time Gospel Hour direct mail list one of the key takeaways here for me is not just that conservatives use technology to further their aims but that there was an alignment between their aims and the technology that they used Manion believed that there were conservatives out there that would support him and his ideas and if he could just specifically target them and build up enough of them he could turn that into a contrary of people that could launch a presidential campaign like Berry Goldwaters I think it's easy for folks today to lose sight of that alignment between aims and tactics people who are doing a lot of activism work may feel like they're having a big impact if they have a big audience on this app for example but they are ultimately being mediated by the algorithm in the app itself Manian could have had a bigger audience if he had just taken sponsorship but he would have had to make compromises Manion picked the right set of tactics for his time and context it was a good lesson then and remains a good lesson today if you're following along we're reading the preface and the first six chapters of before the storm this week and we'll be talking about it on discord see me next week talking more about before the storm if you don't see me in discord sooner

To say this year has been ALOT for me…, would be an understatement.  So much happened in this set of 365 days that i have trouble even remembering it all until i look back at photos and videos, and even then only anout 15% of what happened this year for me was documented via some how.  There were so much core memories made, birthdays, holidays, magazine publications, interviews, new jobs/gigs, concerts, events, new friends, projects, new house and renovations on new house, losing a loved one during the holidays, the list goes on… This year was also a big challange for my mental health and i think a lot of people can agree so i wanted to bring that up. Im ending 2023 really struggling with my mental health, and am really hoping that this new year brings me contentment.  What ever happens in this new year, my main goals are to create more memories with the people i love, work less/live more, find more spaces in time for peace and content, rest my heart. I just want calmness, patience, and time to create art im truly passionate about again in between giving my loved ones more time that they deserve.  So heres to a new year, lets hope its better than the last one!  #2023recap #2023rewind #newyear #happynewyear #happynewyear2024🥂🎄🎉🎁🎇 #2024 #hello2024❤️ #memories #endoftheyear #recap

1) adventuring through the highlands of Papua New Guinea meeting the most mind blowing tribes. Did you know that PNG has almost 1000 languages - meaning you could walk a few hundred yards and they speak a different language!  2 and 3) perhaps the most powerful, intense, and incredible experience of my life as a Sports Envoy with the US State Dept teaching women & children in Papua New Guinea how to surf (and much more). A female is beaten, rapped, or murdered about every 30 seconds in PNG. 4) Swimming with sharks the day after I broke my back in Papua New Guinea - and didn’t know it for another 10 days until I went to an Australian ER. No one can call me a whimp ever again 😜 5) Finally able to sit up after a month on my back in Australia. Sad that I couldn’t complete my Great Barrier Reef conservation adventure - this was my expression of “watch out you never know what life is gonna throw at you - even a surfboard! 6) My adventure home from halfway across the world with 6 duffel bags 4 carry on and 4 surfboards. And I couldn’t walk or lift…. 7) The tragedy of the Maui fires hit home in a very heavy way and we dove into offering aid including securing 100 lbs of insulin, food, baby supplies, ventilators and funds! 8) Whirling from an incredibly traumatic year I decided I just wanted to be a mermaid - and despite everyone making fun of me (including myself) - I posted a minute video on YouTube and earned 30 million views in two weeks - learning that the world could use a little uplifting magical content! 9) I ignored 3 “spam” emails from Kamala Harris and Secretary Blinken inviting us to Washington DC - it wasn’t spam 😜  10) Set off on the first even tri country State Dept Sports Envoy diplomacy mission across Central America teaching kids in remote areas to surf and protect the ocean! Just landed back yesterday and still trying to process the wild, wonderful, intense, and life changing year 2023 has been!  Some lessons learned: - I love to travel but I feel incredibly lucky to be from the USA and hope that those who live privileged lives appreciate every second of it! - when life gets really tough, the best times are right around the corner. - watch out for flying surfboards - It’s important to find your tribe - especially as a female  - Don’t believe everything you see on the news and social media  - If you have a wild whim and decided you just wanna be a mermaid or “do the blender dance” it could lead to great things - BE YOU! - Have something to look forward to in life.  - Call people and see how they are because people can appear like they are living the dream life (including myself) but they actually might be going through a tough time! - You never know what will happen tomorrow - so dive into life, and if feeling lost - do something good for the world - you will find your purpose!

voice_to_text: hey BookTok it's officially January 1st, 2024 I'll probably do more than one sort of wrap up video on not just Simba reading but how the year went um but I thought I'd just start with talking about my top reads for the year I have gone ahead and limited this down to just three books I have read a ton of excellent books this year I'm 4.0 plus average rating for the year which is just excellent but 3 3 books are the standouts and honestly I'm struggling with how I would rank them individually so I might not I might just not do that um the first is Ring Shout by P Djeli Clark this is a novella this is a sort of a an alternative history horror um fantasy novel there are Eldritch style horrors in this this is definitely confronting issues of white supremacy and race and it is stunning uh I think that Ring Shout is a book that everyone should read I think that it's uh just absolutely beautiful and I think it's very very easy to say uh that it is the best uh and most important book that I read this year there were two other books that I thought um fit that in many ways as well um no shocker the will of the mini by James Islington I've talked about this non stop you've seen it on here non stop it'll probably feature in set front and center on my videos uh moving forward this book is fantasy it is epically fast paced considering how thick this book is um the average chapter length is like between six and 10 pages it it's just really lovely I buddy read this with Jordan and Carly and it's just an absolute delight definitely five stars and um a contender again for the top book for this year the last book and the book that I am leaning toward giving the crown for 2023 is Babel by RF Quang there are a lot of reasons why one this book is beautifully uh written it's plot driven uh it focuses on some things that uh some topics that are very poignant and and just so relatable uh in the modern day this is uh a critique of of uh capitalism and colonialism um it speaks a great deal about white supremacy and racism um and also does all of that while focusing really on the art of translating language and what's lost in language this has a very unique magic system um arguably I'd love to have some more detail in the magic system cause I love deep diving on those things but it is just beautifully written uh it there are tons of footnotes in this the narration of this and audio is stunning um this was just excellent heartbreaking at times difficult to read at times extremely poignant another five star read and I think very likely my favorite book of 2023 so I've kept it to three books let me know in the comments what you thought about these books there are so many others to talk about and I will be doing more videos so we'll see you in the next one
